<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-03T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-03T23:00:00-05:00" n="4" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/3260: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-04T04:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">January 4,
                                        1919, 4 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 8:43
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>145. Under date of December 24, 5 p.m., Legation Stockholm informed the
                            Mission that the British, Italian, French Ministers and himself had
                            received letters dated Stockholm, December 23, from <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinoff</persName>, a plenipotentiary of the
                            Russian Federation of Soviets, expressing a desire to enter upon
                            preliminary peace negotiations.</p>
                        <p>For your information. This matter is receiving consideration.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_LR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></persName></signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Mission</hi></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>